What is a Circuit Breaker?
A Circuit Breaker is a design pattern used in distributed systems and microservices to prevent cascading failures.
Imagine one service is failing continuously.
Instead of sending more and more requests to that failing service, the circuit breaker temporarily stops the requests and gives the failing system time to recover.

It works very similar to an electrical circuit breaker in a house.
If too much current flows:
	• the breaker trips, 
	• electricity stops, 
	• damage is prevented. 

In software:
	• too many failed requests happen, 
	• the circuit trips, 
	• requests are blocked, 
	• system damage is prevented. 

Real-World Example
Think about:
	• Netflix 
	• Amazon 
	• Banking apps 
	• Food delivery systems 
Suppose:
	• Your payment service is down. 
	• Thousands of users are trying to pay. 
	• Every request keeps retrying. 
	• Database connections get exhausted. 
	• CPU usage spikes. 
	• Other services also become slow. 
This creates a cascading failure.
Circuit breaker prevents this disaster.

Why Do We Need Circuit Breakers?
Without a circuit breaker:
	1. Requests keep hitting failed service 
	2. Threads become blocked 
	3. Memory increases 
	4. Timeouts increase 
	5. Entire application becomes slow 
	6. Other services start failing too 

This chain reaction is called: Cascading Failure
Circuit breaker helps isolate the failure.

Main Goal
The main goal is:
	“Fail fast instead of failing slowly.”
Instead of waiting 30 seconds for timeout:
	• reject immediately, 
	• return fallback response, 
	• protect the system. 

How Circuit Breaker Works
A circuit breaker has 3 states:

1. Closed State (Normal State)
In this state:
	• Everything works normally. 
	• Requests go to the target service. 
Example:
	• Order Service calls Payment Service 
	• Payment Service responds successfully 
Flow:

User → Order Service → Payment Service → Success
The circuit remains CLOSED.

2. Open State (Failure State)
If failures cross a threshold:
	• circuit breaker OPENS. 
	• Requests are blocked immediately. 
Example:
	• 10 requests fail continuously 
	• Failure threshold exceeded 
	• Circuit opens 
Now:

User → Order Service → Circuit Breaker → Request Blocked
No request reaches Payment Service.
This protects:
	• threads 
	• CPU 
	• memory 
	• network 
	• databases 

3. Half-Open State (Testing State)
After some wait time:
	• circuit breaker allows a few test requests. 
If successful:
	• circuit closes again. 
If failed:
	• circuit opens again. 
This is like checking:
	“Is the service healthy now?”

Complete Lifecycle

Closed → Failures Increase → Open
Open → Wait Time Over → Half Open
Half Open → Success → Closed
Half Open → Failure → Open

Example Scenario
Food Delivery App
Services:
	• Restaurant Service 
	• Payment Service 
	• Notification Service 
	• Delivery Service 
Suppose Payment Service crashes.
Without circuit breaker:
	• millions of requests keep coming 
	• payment service overloaded 
	• threads blocked 
	• application slow 
	• entire app unstable 
With circuit breaker:
	• after threshold failures, 
	• requests stop immediately, 
	• fallback message shown: 

“Payment service temporarily unavailable.”
System survives.

Important Configuration Parameters
1. Failure Threshold
Number of failures before opening circuit.
Example:

If 50% requests fail → Open Circuit

2. Timeout Duration
How long to wait before trying again.
Example:

Wait 30 seconds before Half-Open

3. Sliding Window
Checks failures over a recent time period.
Example:

Last 20 requests

4. Slow Call Threshold
Even slow responses can trigger breaker.
Example:

If response > 5 seconds

Advantages of Circuit Breaker
1. Prevents Cascading Failures
Main benefit.

2. Improves System Stability
Healthy services continue working.

3. Faster Failure Response
No long waiting time.

4. Resource Protection
Protects:
	• CPU 
	• Memory 
	• Thread pools 
	• DB connections 

5. Better User Experience
Users get fallback responses instead of app hanging.

Disadvantages
1. Additional Complexity
More configurations and monitoring needed.

2. Wrong Thresholds Can Cause Problems
Too sensitive:
	• opens unnecessarily 
Too relaxed:
	• failures continue too long 

Circuit Breaker vs Retry
Feature	Retry	Circuit Breaker
Purpose	Retry failed request	Stop failed requests
Goal	Recover temporary failure	Prevent overload
Behavior	Sends more requests	Blocks requests
Risk	Can increase load	Reduces load
Usually both are used together carefully.

Circuit Breaker + Retry Combination
Best practice:
	1. Retry few times 
	2. If still failing 
	3. Circuit breaker opens 
Example:

Retry 3 times
Still failing?
Open circuit

